node.contents: Since other answers showed how to do it with Collections.shuffle() already - here is a simple implementation + example of fisher yates shuffle, that does not need to convert the original array into a list.

astNode.text: Since other answers showed how to do it with Collections.shuffle() already - here is a simple implementation + example of fisher yates shuffle, that does not need to convert the original array into a list.

elements.contents: private static void swap (int[] arr, int i1, int i2) { int temp = arr[i1]; arr[i1] = arr[i2]; arr[i2] = temp; } private static void shuffle(int[] arr, Random r) { for (int i =0; i < arr.length; i++) { int x = r.nextInt(arr.length - i) + i; swap(arr,i,x); } } public static void main(String... args) throws Exception { int[] arr = new int[] {1 , 5, 6, 3, 0, 11,2,9 }; shuffle(arr, new Random()); System.out.println(Arrays.toString(arr)); }

units.rawText: private static void swap (int[] arr, int i1, int i2) { int temp = arr[i1]; arr[i1] = arr[i2]; arr[i2] = temp; } private static void shuffle(int[] arr, Random r) { for (int i =0; i < arr.length; i++) { int x = r.nextInt(arr.length - i) + i; swap(arr,i,x); } } public static void main(String... args) throws Exception { int[] arr = new int[] {1, 5, 6, 3, 0, 11,2,9}; shuffle(arr, new Random()); System.out.println(Arrays.toString(arr)); }

elements.contents: public static void main(String[] args) { List<Integer> a = new ArrayList<>(9); for (int i = 0; i < 9; i++) { a.add(i); } Collections.shuffle(a); System.out.println(a); }
